summary:
Studijoje analizuojami XVI amžiaus pabaigoje ir XVII amžiaus pradžioje atlikti LDK žemėlapio sudarymo ir leidybos darbai. Išskiriami LDK kartografavimo darbų pagrindiniai etapai. Tai - 
1. lauko kartografavimo darbai ir LDK žemėlapio autorinio originialo braižymas; apie 1590 - 1600m.;
2. LDK žemėlapio leidybinio originalo braižymas ir žemėlapio spausdinimas; apie 1600 - 1603 m.; šioje studijoje žemėlapis sąlyginiai įvardintas kaip LDK 1603m. žemėlapis;
3. LDK 1603 m. žemėlapio tobulinimo darbai, atlikti po 1603m.; išbraižytas būsimo LDK 1613m. žemėlapio autorinis originalas;
4. LDK 1613m. žemėlapio spausdinimas Amsterdame, V. J. Blau leidykloje.
Apie pirmąjį ir antrąjį darbų etapus rašoma pirmoje studijos dalyje, o apie trečiąjį ir ketvirtąjį - antroje studijos dalyje. Trečioje studijos dalyje aprašomi XVIII a. ir XIX a. bibliografiniai leidiniai, kuriuose įrašyti žemėlapiai. Taip pat analizuojamos LDK 1613 m. žemėlapio studijos, atliktos XX a. ir XXI a. pradžioje.

ISBN 978-609-8192-14-8

In Mediterranean Area, the interest in geography and maps that had begun in the 2ⁿᵈ century with the Greco-Roman scholar Klaudios Ptolemaios increasingly grew in later periods and unique collections of maps of the 15th and 16th century were assembled in museums, palaces and private collections. In these centuries, Mediterranean was common area of observation, study and science for Latin and Turkish seamen and cartographer. Tunuslu İbrâhim Kâtibî (Ibrahim Katibi of Tunis), Mürsiyeli İbrâhim (Ibrahim of Murcia), El-Hacc Ebu’l Hasan, Gabriel Devallsecha, Jacobus Russus of Messina, Giorgio Sideri (Callapoda Da Candia) and other seamen / cartographers drew maps and portolans. These portolans provides us with the geographical properties of the Mediterranean coasts, information on the cities and the life of people. They represent of interaction between Ottoman and Latin artists who had the important values of Mediterranean arts too. The present paper aims to study the below portolans: 
A- Portolans drawn by Ottoman cartographers: 
Mediterranean Portolan (1413-14) of Tunuslu İbrâhim Kâtibî (Ibrahim Katibi of Tunis); 
Mediterranean Portolan (1461) of Mürsiyeli İbrâhim (Ibrahim of Murcia); 
Mediterranean Portolan (1570?) of El-Hacc Ebu’l Hasan.  
B- Portolans drawn by Latin cartographers: 
Mediterranean Portolan (1447) of Gabriel Devallsecha;  
Mediterranean Portolan (1533) of Jacobus Russus of Messina; 
Mediterranean Portolan (1565) of Giorgio Sideri (Callapoda Da Candia).

The “Historical Geocoding Assistant” is an open-source browser-based application for assigning geographic coordinates in a more convenient and faster way than copy-pasting them from services such as Google Maps. The application was designed with historical projects in mind but is suitable for any geocoding work. Essential features:
- works online with a live Google Spreadsheets table;
- gathers suggestions of coordinates from gazetteers for instant use (GeoNames, Wikipedia, Getty Thesaurus of Geographic Names, Pleiades, and China Historical GIS);
- integrates search services (Google Maps, Google Search, Peripleo);
- supports multiple base layers (OpenStreetMap, satellite images, Imperium, etc.);
- supports multiple overlay layers;
- allows setting relevant spatial extent;
- allows spatial uncertainty levels.
